Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Zhiqing Su

2023-03-12

My meme

My meme is a smiling cat. There is some words at the top and the bottom of my meme which form a sentence to encourage you. I also used two letters, and the eyes of the cat to form a word cool.

library(magick)

#Smiling cat(base image), image source:https://i.pinimg.com/originals/ba/92/7f/ba927ff34cd961ce2c184d47e8ead9f6.jpg
cat_meme <- image_read("cat.jpeg") %>%
  image_scale("500x500")

#Top text 
top_text <- image_blank(width = 500,
                        height = 80,
                        color = "#FFFACD") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Did you know that",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 50,
                 gravity = "center")

#Bottom text
bottom_text <- image_blank(width = 500,
                           height = 80,
                           color = "#FFFACD") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "you are the best",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 50,
                 gravity = "center") 

#Create a new image with text
image_with_text <- image_annotate(cat_meme, text = "C", color = "#FF7F50", size = 80, location = "+20+150") %>%
  image_annotate( text = "L", color = "#FF7F50", size = 80, location = "+390+140")

#Combine top text, bottom text and new image
cat_meme <- c(top_text, image_with_text, bottom_text) %>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE)

#Save image
image_write(cat_meme, "smiling_cat_meme.png")

My animated GIF

This is a opening fragment of a vlog. I use a picture as the background and two blank text to form a progress bar, and the progress bar grows until it is finished. Finally, there will be a sentence Welcome to my vlog! show on the background.

library(magick)

# Select a picture as the background.
background <- image_read("background.png") %>%
  image_scale("750x500")

# The progress bar and some text on the background.
frame1 <- image_annotate(background, text = "          ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#9370DB", location = "+240+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "                ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#E6E6FA", location = "+350+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Loading.", size = 50, color = "#BA55D3", location = "+330+240")

# The progress bar and some text on the background.
frame2 <- image_annotate(background, text = "              ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#9370DB", location = "+240+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "         ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#E6E6FA", location = "+469+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Loading..", size = 50, color = "#BA55D3", location = "+330+240")

# The progress bar and some text on the background.
frame3 <- image_annotate(background, text = "                  ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#9370DB", location = "+240+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "     ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#E6E6FA", location = "+537+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Loading...", size = 50, color = "#BA55D3", location = "+330+240")

# The progress bar and some text on the background.
frame4 <- image_annotate(background, text = "                       ", size = 60, boxcolor = "#9370DB", location = "+240+150") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Complete!", size = 50, color = "#BA55D3", location = "+330+240")

# The progress bar is finished, and only the text on the background.
frame5 <- image_annotate(background, text = "Welcome to my vlog!", size = 50, color = "#BA55D3", location = "+200+150")



# Combine different frames.
final_frame <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4, frame5)
# Form an animate.
gif <- image_animate(final_frame, fps = 1)
# Save the gif.
image_write(gif, "my_animation.gif")

My CSS

This is my css!

  1. Title font: Mulish

  2. Body font: Indie Flower

  3. Background color: #E6E6FA

@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Climate+Crisis&family=Genos:wght@500&family=IBM+Plex+Mono:wght@300&family=Indie+Flower&family=Lobster&display=swap');
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Climate+Crisis&family=Genos:wght@500&family=IBM+Plex+Mono:wght@300&family=Indie+Flower&family=Lobster&family=Mulish&display=swap');
